The paper discusses a software tool for brain imaging using finite element method and graphics processing unit acceleration. This falls under the category of computational neuroscience (cs.NE) and could also be relevant to computer vision (cs.CV) and human-computer interaction (cs.HC) due to the potential applications of brain imaging. The use of GPU acceleration also suggests a potential connection to computer engineering (cs.CE) and the use of statistical models for inverse computations could be relevant to machine learning (cs.MS).
